* The [[Treaty of Lausanne]] in 1923 included the list of [[150 personae non gratae of Turkey|150 ''personae non gratae'' of Turkey]], which forbade the entry of mainly a group of former [[Ottoman Empire]] officials and about 100 other persons to [[Turkey]], until the lifting of this status in 1938.{{Citation needed|date=March 2012}} * [[Chiune Sugihara]], who helped several thousand Jews in Lithuania in the 1940s, was declared ''persona non grata'' by the Soviet Union in 1947.{{citation needed|date=July 2014}} * [[Queen Victoria Eugenie of Spain]] was obliged to leave Italy in 1942 having become ''persona non grata'' to the Italian government. According to [[Harold Tittmann]], a United States representative at the Vatican at the time, this was due to her "ill-disguised leanings to the Allied cause."<ref>Harold Tittmann, ''Inside the Vatican of Pius XI'', p. 32, Image book, Doubleday, 2004.</ref> * [[Harald Edelstam]], Swedish ambassador to Chile, was declared ''persona non grata'' for his efforts to hide and assist members of the opposition facing persecution by the [[Military dictatorship of Chile (1973–1990)|Chilean junta]] of 1973–1990, including occupying the Embassy of [[Cuba]] in [[Santiago]], containing hundreds of refugees, and declaring it Swedish soil. * [[Kurt Waldheim]], former [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]] and [[President of Austria]], and his wife were given ''persona non grata'' status in the United States and other countries when he was accused of having known about [[Nazi war crime]]s and not having done anything about them.<ref name="waldheim1">{{cite news |url=http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/w/kurt_waldheim/index.html |title=Kurt Waldheim |access-date=January 1, 2009 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|first=Serge|last=Schmemann}}</ref> * In September 1952, the American Ambassador to the Soviet Union, [[George F. Kennan]], was declared ''persona non grata'' after making a statement which the Soviets believed linked them to Nazi Germany. The Soviets refused to allow Kennan to reenter the Soviet Union.<ref>Kennan, George F. (1967), ''Memoirs: 1925–1950'', Boston: Little, Brown and Company, OCLC 484922. 152</ref> * In March 1976, [[Herbert Spiro]], the [[United States Ambassador to Cameroon]], also [[United States Ambassador to Equatorial Guinea|accredited to Equatorial Guinea]], was declared ''persona non grata'' by Equatorial Guinea. At the end of a visit to the country which he described as pleasant and uneventful up to that point, Equatoguinean Deputy Protocol Director [[Santiago Nchama]] handed him a letter accusing the United States government of engaging in subversive activities there, and days later, [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs and International Cooperation (Equatorial Guinea)|Equatorial Guinea's foreign ministry]] sent a telegram to the State Department announcing that Spiro and Consul William C. Mithoefer Jr, who had accompanied him on his visit, were both barred from the country.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=2199&dat=19760315&id=sP0xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=YuUFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6878,2150846|title=Snub snaps U.S. ties with Equatorial Guinea|work=Lawrence Journal-World|date=March 15, 1976|access-date=June 9, 2014}}</ref> * In April 1979, the [[Central Intelligence Agency]]'s expert on [[Iran]], [[George Cave (CIA agent)|George W. Cave]], was declared ''persona non grata'' by the [[Iranian government]].<ref name="Participant Biographies">{{cite web |url=http://www.wilsoncenter.org/sites/default/files/Iran%20conference%20bios.pdf |title=The Cold War International History Project / The National Security Archive / The Middle East Program&nbsp;— Participant Biographies |author=<!-- Staff writer(s); no by-line. --> |date= |website=www.wilsoncenter.org |publisher=Woodrow Wilson International Center for Scholars |access-date=March 12, 2015}}</ref> * In the 1990s, [[Mario Vargas Llosa]], who would later receive the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]], was "''persona non grata'' in [[Peru]], discredited and insulted in the official press" of [[Alberto Fujimori]]'s regime. According to [[Ilan Stavans]], "Peruvians have made it a sport to hate Vargas Llosa."<ref>{{cite news|authorlink=Maya Jaggi|first=Maya|last=Jaggi|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2002/mar/16/fiction.books?INTCMP=SRCH|title=Fiction and hyper-reality|newspaper=The Guardian|date=March 16, 2002|quote="During Fujimori's first two years I was very discreet," he says. "But I've been against dictatorships all my life. My situation became very difficult: I was persona non grata in Peru, discredited and insulted in the official press&nbsp;— Fujimori controlled everything. It was difficult because I couldn't respond."}}</ref> * In 1995, [[Croatia]] declared [[Carl Bildt]] ''persona non grata'' announcing that he had "lost the credibility necessary for the role of a peace mediator". Bildt had suggested that the President of Croatia, [[Franjo Tuđman]] was as guilty of war crimes as the Krajina Serb leader, [[Milan Martić]].<ref name="bnetcroatia">{{cite web|url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_/ai_n13999209 |title=Flight from Croatia: Refugee column hit from the air |access-date=January 1, 2009 |author=Emma Daly |date=August 8, 1995 |publisher=BNET |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130814170424/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_qn4158/is_/ai_n13999209 |archivedate=August 14, 2013 |df=}} </ref> * [[Brad Pitt]] became ''persona non grata'' in the [[People's Republic of China]] after he appeared in the 1997 film ''[[Seven Years in Tibet (1997 film)|Seven Years in Tibet]]''. The ban was lifted in 2014 when he accompanied his wife [[Angelina Jolie]] on a film promotion tour.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Chinafilminsider.com|date=October 27, 2016|access-date=July 19, 2018|url=http://chinafilminsider.com/brad-pitt-set-promote-allied-china-ending-two-decade-ban/|title=Brad Pitt Set To Promote ‘Allied’ In China, Ending Two-Decade ‘Ban’